File: Insurance. Pixabay/stevepb JOHANNESBURG - State insurer Sasria is warning that it cannot afford to cover the country’s businesses should it see a repeat of last year's unrest. In a presentation to Parliament, Sasria executives said that the group's current balance sheet is not adequate for another R30-billion loss. READ: July unrest | Sasria pays out R12.5bn in claims The state insurer says early warning signals point to another loss if interventions are not urgently put in place. The country took a huge hit in investor confidence when the unrest unfolded last year. As part of its response, government is set to enrol 12,000 police officers before the end of this year.